MYCOPLASMA GALLISEPTICUM, AVIAN - USA (03): (ILLINOIS), COMMENT
***************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 27 Feb 2013
Source: Ellen Hooker <Ellen.Hooker@wisconsin.gov> [edited]


I am not sure whether the feral cat population should be held in such high esteem as to be responsible for "controlling" _M. gallicepticum_ in wild birds. I suggest that ProMED solicit input from the Association of Avian Veterinarians or Cats Indoors to get their input on feral cat effects on wild birds. Hawaii, for example, has had a precipitous decline in their endangered song birds due to feral cat colonies, and now toxoplasmosis is affecting endangered Hawaiian Monk Seal populations.

--
Ellen Hooker DVM
District Veterinarian
DATCP-Division of Animal Health
Waupaca WI
<Ellen.Hooker@wisconsin.gov>

[ProMED-mail thanks Dr. Hooker for this contribution. - Mod.PMB

